      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Don't Mar the Mall'' (editorial, Sept. 24):</p>
        <p>I am a citizen who considers separation of church and state a basic tenet of our Republic. Yet I ask: if one would choose a word to describe the land between the Washington Monument and the Lincoln Memorial, would not that word be ''sacred''?</p>
        <p>The line of vision from the Capitol to the Obelisk to Lincoln should remain unbroken -- a symbol, to every generation, of the uncompromising vision of our founding fathers and of Lincoln  and their establishment and preservation of our country and Union.</p>
        <p>World War II veterans certainly deserve a memorial in recognition of their bravery, their sacrifices and their patriotism. That memorial should be built, however, on a site other than the one planned.</p>
        <p>ALICE KATZ BERGLAS  New York, Sept. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
